## Boundaries & Limits
Explicit min/max, field lengths, decimal precision, ranges, counts, allowed value sets,
timeouts. "Not specified" where the document gives no limit.

## Data Requirements
Key entities and their important fields: type, mandatory vs optional, defaults — as stated.
Mark unknowns "Not specified".

## Integration & External Dependencies
APIs, third-party/downstream systems, and what depends on them, with any error codes given.

## Error & Exception Scenarios
What can go wrong and the system's required response, with exact messages/codes where stated.
Mark inferred entries "(inferred)".

## Non-Functional Requirements
Performance, security, accessibility, compatibility — ONLY where the document addresses them.
If silent, write "Not specified in document" rather than listing generic best practices.

## Assumptions & Inferred Requirements
Consolidated list of everything marked "(inferred)" for the team to confirm.

## Open Questions / Ambiguities
Gaps, contradictions, undefined terms, missing rules QA must clarify. Phrase as questions.
Put uncertainty here — do not resolve it by guessing elsewhere.

## QA Test Coverage Areas
Per module, the consolidated scenarios the document justifies, using the suite's style:
